\section{Tectonics and Mechanical Legibility}

\subsection{Expressing Mechanical Logic Through Form}
Tectonics, as a design philosophy, holds that the constructional logic of an artifact should be expressed in its form. For a hand, this means:
\begin{itemize}
\item Tendon paths should be visible where feasible, showing how force is transmitted.
\item Joints should be articulated clearly, revealing degrees of freedom.
\item Actuators should be located in a way that communicates their role.
\item Sensors should be integrated as deliberate design elements.
\end{itemize}

While tectonics originates in architecture, its principles align with a critical need in modern Human-Robot Interaction (HRI): \emph{mechanical legibility}. \citet{dragan2013legibility} define legibility as the ability of an observer to quickly and confidently infer a robot's goal from its motion. We extend this concept from \emph{motion} to \emph{structure}. A tectonically designed hand is mechanically legible—its form communicates its function, reducing the cognitive load on the user and potentially increasing trust \citep{hoffman2013expressive}. Thus, our tectonic proxies are not merely aesthetic metrics but proxies for cognitive accessibility.

\subsection{Quantitative Proxies for Tectonic Qualities}
To make tectonic design actionable, we propose quantitative proxies:

\begin{definition}[Tendon Visibility Index (TVI)]
\[
\TVI = \frac{L_{\text{exposed}}}{L_{\text{total}}} \cdot \frac{1}{1 + \text{sheath\_opacity}}
\]
where \(L_{\text{exposed}}\) is the length of visible tendon, \(L_{\text{total}}\) is total tendon length, and \(\text{sheath\_opacity} \in [0,1]\) measures how much sheathing conceals the tendon. The denominator reflects that opaque sheathing reduces visibility nonlinearly; the linear form is a first approximation.
\end{definition}

\begin{definition}[Articulation Exposure Score (AES)]
\[
\AES = \frac{\sum_i \text{exposed\_DOF}_i \cdot w_i}{\sum_i \text{total\_DOF}_i \cdot w_i}
\]
where \(\text{exposed\_DOF}_i\) counts degrees of freedom at joint \(i\) that are visibly articulated, and \(w_i\) weights joints by importance (e.g., derived from grasp frequency or biomechanical significance).
\end{definition}

\begin{definition}[Force Flow Clarity (FFC)]
\[
\FFC = \frac{1}{1 + \text{path\_curvature} + \text{hidden\_guides}}
\]
where \(\text{path\_curvature}\) measures deviation from straight lines (e.g., total curvature integrated along tendon path), and \(\text{hidden\_guides}\) counts concealed redirection points (pulleys). This metric assumes that straight, visible force paths are more legible.
\end{definition}

These proxies can be incorporated into multi-objective optimization alongside functional metrics, enabling trade-off analysis between tectonic expression and other design goals.

\subsection{Tendon‑Driven Systems as Tectonic Elements}
Tendon‑driven systems have inherent tectonic qualities. The tension elements contrast with compression elements (finger links), creating visual tension that communicates force flow. Pulleys become expressive joints, redirecting tendons in visible ways. A tectonically designed hand reveals its operation through its appearance.

\textit{Design Guidelines:}
\begin{itemize}
\item Use transparent or translucent sheathing where tendon concealment is necessary.
\item Expose tendons at joints to show redirection.
\item Design pulleys as visible, expressive elements rather than hiding them within links.
\item Color-code tendon groups by function (flexion, extension, abduction).
\item Express stiffness differences through material choices (compliant sections visually distinct from rigid).
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Aesthetic and Psychological Dimensions}
For prosthetic hands especially, aesthetic considerations are crucial. Users must be comfortable wearing the device in social situations. A tectonic approach offers a middle path between realistic (cosmetic) prosthetics and purely mechanical devices: rather than hiding mechanics, it celebrates mechanical logic while achieving visual harmony through proportion, material quality, and detail refinement.

Studies \citep{biddiss2008upper, cordella2016literature} show that prosthetic abandonment correlates strongly with appearance and perceived naturalness. Tectonic design addresses these factors by making the mechanical logic legible and aesthetically coherent, potentially improving acceptance rates.

\section{Adaptability as a Design Philosophy}

\subsection{Layered Adaptability in Architecture and Robotics}
\citet{brand1994how} concept of layered adaptability applies directly to hand design:
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Kinematic structure:} Changes rarely (if at all) during the hand's lifetime (shearing layers: structure).
\item \textbf{Actuation system:} May be upgraded or reconfigured on a longer timescale (services).
\item \textbf{Sensing layer:} Can be augmented with additional sensors (space plan).
\item \textbf{Control software:} Can be updated frequently (stuff).
\item \textbf{Grasp strategies:} Adapt in real time to task demands (stuff).
\end{itemize}
Designing for adaptability means considering all these layers and their interactions.

\subsection{Polyvalence and Underactuation}
\citet{hertzberger2005lessons} polyvalence—designing elements that accommodate multiple uses without physical change—is realized in underactuated fingers. A well‑designed underactuated finger adapts to different object shapes without requiring active control of each joint. The passive mechanics provide polyvalence.

We propose a polyvalence index for an underactuated finger:
\[
\PI = \frac{\text{Number of distinct graspable object classes}}{\text{Number of actuators}}.
\]
Higher \(\PI\) indicates greater polyvalence—more functional variety per actuator. The object classes could be defined by shape, size, or compliance, based on a taxonomy such as that of \citet{cutkosky1989grasp}.

\subsection{Designing for Multiple Timescales}
The mathematical framework of Chapter 3, with its separation of kinematic, dynamic, and control layers, naturally supports layered adaptability. The port‑Hamiltonian formulation, in particular, allows modular composition and replacement of subsystems, facilitating design changes at different timescales.

\chapter{Integration of Mathematical and Architectural Representations}
\label{chap:integration}

\section{Formal Mappings Between Representations}

\subsection{From Joint Angles to Design Patterns}
Given a joint‑angle vector \(\theta\), we can identify which design pattern(s) it instantiates through a nearest-neighbor classification in configuration space:

\begin{enumerate}
\item Define pattern templates \(R_k\) as regions in joint‑angle space: \(R_k = \{\theta: \theta^{\min}_k \leq \theta \leq \theta^{\max}_k,\ \text{force\_closure}(\theta) = \text{True}\}\).
\item Compute distance \(d(\theta, R_k) = \min_{\theta' \in R_k} \|\theta - \theta'\|_W\), where \(W\) weights joints by importance (e.g., derived from the pattern's own importance weights).
\item Classify \(\theta\) as pattern \(k\) if \(d(\theta, R_k) < \epsilon\) and \(\epsilon\) is smallest across all \(k\).
\end{enumerate}

For patterns with continuous parameters (e.g., grasp size), we also compute the best-fit parameters via optimization:
\[
\min_{\alpha} \|\theta - \theta_k(\alpha)\|^2 \ \text{ subject to } \theta_k(\alpha) \in R_k.
\]

Conversely, given a pattern \(p\) and parameters \(\alpha\) (e.g., object size), we generate a representative \(\theta\) through inverse kinematics or optimization:
\[
\min_{\theta} \|T(\theta) - T_{\text{desired}}\|^2 \ \text{ subject to pattern constraints}.
\]

\subsection{From Spatial Grammar to Kinematic Constraints}
A spatial grammar rule, such as \(\operatorname{Par}(\operatorname{Flex}(\phi_1, j_1), \operatorname{Flex}(\phi_2, j_2))\), imposes constraints on the joint angles: \(\theta_{j_1} = \phi_1\), \(\theta_{j_2} = \phi_2\). More complex rules may involve inequalities (e.g., \(\operatorname{Cond}(\text{contact}, \text{Stop}, \text{Continue})\)). These constraints define admissible subsets of the configuration space.

The grammar generates a constraint satisfaction problem (CSP) that can be solved numerically:
\[
\text{Given grammar } G \text{ and start configuration } \theta_0, \text{ find } \theta \text{ such that } \theta = G(\theta_0) \text{ satisfies all constraints}.
\]

\subsection{Tectonic Qualities and Mechanical Parameters}
Tectonic qualities relate to mechanical parameters through the proxies defined in Section 4.3.2:
\begin{align*}
\TVI &= f(\text{routing geometry, sheath material}), \\
\AES &= g(\text{joint cover design, bearing exposure}), \\
\FFC &= h(\text{path curvature, guide visibility}).
\end{align*}
These relationships are implemented as functions mapping CAD parameters to tectonic scores, enabling theoretical optimization:
\[
\min_{\text{design parameters}} \big[ w_1 \cdot \text{functional\_cost} + w_2 \cdot \text{tectonic\_cost} \big].
\]

\subsection{Towards a Functorial Semantics}
The relationship between the mathematical model \(\mathcal{M}\) (a Lie group \(\mathcal{C}\) with dynamics) and the design model \(\mathcal{D}\) (a pattern language \(\mathcal{L}\) with grammar \(\mathcal{G}\)) can be rigorously understood as a functor \(F: \mathcal{D} \to \mathcal{M}\) between categories. The objects of \(\mathcal{D}\) are design patterns, with morphisms representing refinement or composition (e.g., a pattern refined into sub-patterns). The objects of \(\mathcal{M}\) are submanifolds of \(\mathcal{C}\) satisfying kinematic constraints (e.g., the set of configurations that realize a given pattern). The functor \(F\) maps each pattern \(p\) to its admissible configuration space \(F(p) \subset \mathcal{C}\), and each design refinement to an inclusion map between submanifolds. This ensures that the composition of design rules corresponds to the intersection of configuration subspaces, preserving structural relationships.

This categorical perspective, while not fully developed here, points toward a deeper unification where the algebraic structure of design mirrors the geometric structure of motion.

\section{Dual Representation and Design Space Exploration}

\subsection{Maintaining Both Descriptions Simultaneously}
A dual representation maintains both the mathematical description \((\theta, P, M, \text{etc.})\) and the design description (pattern instances, grammar rules, tectonic qualities) simultaneously through a unified data structure:

\begin{verbatim}
class HandDesign:
    # Mathematical representation
    joint_angles: np.ndarray
    coupling_matrix: np.ndarray
    inertia_matrix: np.ndarray
    hamiltonian: Function

    # Design representation
    patterns: List[Pattern]
    grammar_history: List[Rule]
    tectonic_scores: Dict[str, float]

    # Mappings
    def to_patterns(self): ...
    def from_pattern(self, pattern, params): ...
    def tectonic_evaluate(self): ...
\end{verbatim}

This allows:
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Analysis:} Starting from a mathematical model, identify the design patterns it supports.
\item \textbf{Synthesis:} Starting from a design concept, generate mathematical models that realize it.
\item \textbf{Iteration:} Modify one representation and see the effect on the other.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Exploring Design Alternatives with Mathematical Guidance}
Design space exploration combines mathematical optimization with design reasoning:

\begin{enumerate}
\item Define a set of candidate design patterns (from the pattern language).
\item For each pattern, generate a family of mathematical models parameterized by continuous variables (e.g., joint ranges, spring constants, coupling ratios).
\item Use optimization to find parameter values that satisfy constraints and optimize performance metrics (e.g., adaptation index, grasp stability).
\item Evaluate the resulting designs against tectonic criteria (\(\TVI\), \(\AES\), \(\FFC\)).
\item Iterate, refining patterns and parameters.
\end{enumerate}

\textit{Optimization Formulation:}
\[
\min_{x} [f_1(x), f_2(x), f_3(x)]
\]
subject to:
\begin{align*}
g_j(x) &\leq 0 \quad \text{(kinematic constraints)}\\
h_k(x) &= 0 \quad \text{(pattern-specific constraints)}\\
x &\in \mathcal{X} \quad \text{(design parameter bounds)}
\end{align*}
where \(f_1 = \text{functional cost (e.g., }-\AI\text{)}\), \(f_2 = -\CI\) (for desired synergies), \(f_3 = -\text{tectonic scores}\).

\subsection{Pareto Optimal Design Exploration}
We now demonstrate the dual representation through a Pareto optimization of a 2-DOF underactuated finger (MCP and PIP joints, one actuator). The design variables are the coupling ratio \(k\) in \(P = [1, k]^T\) and a binary variable \(s\) indicating whether tendons are sheathed (opacity 0.8) or exposed (opacity 0). We define two objectives:

\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Functional:} Maximize coupling index \(\CI(P, c)\) for a desired power grasp synergy \(c = [1,1]^T\). For a 2-DOF finger, \(\CI(P,c) = \frac{|1+k|}{\sqrt{2(1+k^2)}}\).

\item \textbf{Tectonic:} Maximize mechanical legibility \(\ML = \alpha \TVI + \beta \AES + \gamma \FFC\). For simplicity, we set \(\ML = \TVI\) (since sheathing is the main variable). \(\TVI = 1/(1+s\cdot 0.8)\) where \(s=1\) if sheathed, \(0\) if exposed.
\end{itemize}

We sweep \(k\) from 0.1 to 1.0 and \(s\in\{0,1\}\). Figure 5.1 shows the Pareto frontier: designs with exposed tendons (high \(\TVI\)) tend to have slightly lower \(\CI\) because exposed routing may force less optimal coupling (here we assume exposed routing does not affect \(k\), but in reality it might). The frontier reveals that for a desired \(\CI\), the best tectonic design is the one with highest \(\TVI\), and vice versa.

This simple example illustrates how the framework enables quantitative trade-off analysis. In a full design scenario, more variables and objectives would be considered.

\section{Implications for Prosthetic and Robotic Hand Design}

\subsection{Human‑Centered Design Principles}
The integrated framework supports human‑centered design by:
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Involving users early:} Pattern language provides a vocabulary for users to express needs.
\item \textbf{Iterative prototyping:} Dual representation enables rapid exploration of alternatives.
\item \textbf{Aesthetic integration:} Tectonic principles ensure that functional design also yields pleasing form.
\item \textbf{Customization:} Patterns can be selected and parameterized for individual user needs.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Bridging Mathematical Optimization and User Acceptance}
Mathematical optimization can produce highly functional designs, but user acceptance depends on factors beyond raw performance. The framework bridges this gap by:
\begin{itemize}
\item Encoding user preferences as constraints or objectives in the optimization (e.g., "visibility of moving parts" as tectonic score).
\item Using pattern languages to ensure designs align with user expectations (e.g., "this should move like a human finger").
\item Applying tectonic principles to create visually appealing devices that communicate their function.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Toward a Unified Design Methodology}
The integrated framework suggests a unified methodology for hand design:

\begin{enumerate}
\item \textbf{Requirements analysis:} Use pattern language to capture user needs and task contexts.
\item \textbf{Concept generation:} Use spatial grammar to generate alternative configurations.
\item \textbf{Mathematical modeling:} Develop kinematic and dynamic models for each concept.
\item \textbf{Optimization:} Refine parameters to meet performance targets using the adaptation index and other metrics.
\item \textbf{Tectonic refinement:} Adjust design to enhance expression and aesthetics using quantitative proxies.
\item \textbf{Iteration:} Return to concept generation or modeling as needed.
\end{enumerate}

This methodology combines the rigor of mathematics with the creativity of design, leading to hands that are both highly functional and deeply human‑centered.

\section{Computational Algorithms for Dual Representation}
To operationalize the dual representation, we provide algorithmic descriptions that formalize the mappings between mathematical and design spaces. These algorithms are implemented in the supplementary code.

\subsection{POE Kinematics Algorithm}
\begin{verbatim}
def poe_forward_kinematics(screw_axes, theta, M):
    T = M
    for i in reversed(range(len(theta))):
        T = exp_twist(screw_axes[i], theta[i]) @ T
    return T

def exp_twist(screw, theta):
    omega = screw[3:]
    v = screw[:3]
    theta_norm = norm(omega)
    if theta_norm < 1e-6:
        R = eye(3)
        p = v * theta
    else:
        omega_hat = skew(omega)
        R = eye(3) + sin(theta_norm)/theta_norm * omega_hat + \
            (1 - cos(theta_norm))/theta_norm**2 * (omega_hat @ omega_hat)
        p = (eye(3) - R) @ cross(omega, v) + omega @ omega.T @ v * theta_norm
    return construct_SE3(R, p)
\end{verbatim}

\subsection{Port-Hamiltonian Dynamics Formulation}
\begin{verbatim}
def port_hamiltonian_dynamics(t, x, params):
    q = x[:n]; p = x[n:2*n]; ell = x[2*n:]

    H = 0.5 * p @ inv(M(q)) @ p + V(q) + 0.5 * ell @ K_e @ ell
    dH_dq = grad_V(q) + 0.5 * p @ d_invM_dq(q) @ p
    dH_dp = inv(M(q)) @ p
    dH_dell = K_e @ ell

    J = [[0, I, 0],
         [-I, 0, 0],
         [0, 0, 0]]
    R = diag([0, D, R_tendon])

    B = [0; P(q).T; 0]
    u = control_law(t, q, p, ell)

    dx = (J - R) @ [dH_dq; dH_dp; dH_dell] + B @ u
    return dx
\end{verbatim}

\subsection{Pattern Classification Algorithm}
\begin{verbatim}
def classify_grasp(theta, pattern_library, W):
    best_pattern = None
    min_dist = inf
    for pattern in pattern_library:
        if any(theta < pattern.theta_min) or any(theta > pattern.theta_max):
            continue
        if not force_closure(theta, pattern.object):
            continue
        diff = theta - pattern.nominal
        dist = sqrt(sum(W * diff**2))
        if dist < min_dist:
            min_dist = dist
            best_pattern = pattern
    return best_pattern, min_dist
\end{verbatim}

\subsection{Tectonic Score Calculation}
\begin{verbatim}
def tectonic_scores(design):
    exposed_length = sum(seg.length for seg in design.tendons if seg.visible)
    total_length = sum(seg.length for seg in design.tendons)
    sheath_opacity = mean([seg.sheath.opacity for seg in design.tendons
                           if hasattr(seg, 'sheath')])
    TVI = (exposed_length / total_length) / (1 + sheath_opacity)

    aes_numer = 0
    aes_denom = 0
    for joint in design.joints:
        aes_numer += joint.exposed_dof * joint.importance
        aes_denom += joint.total_dof * joint.importance
    AES = aes_numer / aes_denom if aes_denom > 0 else 0

    path_curvature = mean([seg.curvature for seg in design.tendons])
    hidden_guides = sum(1 for guide in design.pulleys if guide.hidden)
    FFC = 1 / (1 + path_curvature + hidden_guides)

    return {'TVI': TVI, 'AES': AES, 'FFC': FFC}
\end{verbatim}

These algorithms provide a theoretical foundation for implementing the dual representation in software, enabling automated exploration of the design space defined by the integrated framework.

\chapter{Conclusion}
\label{chap:conclusion}

\section{Summary of Contributions}
This dissertation has developed a unified theoretical framework that integrates geometric mechanics with architectural‑design thinking for hand finger movement analysis. Building upon prior work in port-Hamiltonian finger modeling \citep{wassink2010port} and screw-theoretic hand analysis \citep{dai2009metamorphic}, the contributions are:

\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Contribution 1: A Unified Geometric Framework.} A comprehensive description of hand kinematics and dynamics using screw theory, Lie groups, and port‑Hamiltonian systems, extending prior applications to include variable transmission, reconfiguration, and design-oriented extensions. The framework captures both continuous motion and the discrete aspects of underactuation, providing a rigorous foundation for analysis and design.

\item \textbf{Contribution 2: Formal Characterization of the Coupling–Adaptation Paradox.} A novel geometric characterization of the fundamental trade-off in underactuated finger design, including the adaptation index \(\AI(P) = \dim(\ker(P^T))/\rank(P)\) that quantifies adaptive potential, and a theorem establishing the inherent conflict between coupling and adaptation, distinguished from classical manipulability.

\item \textbf{Contribution 3: A Spatial Grammar for Hand Movements.} A formal rule‑based system for generating and describing hand configurations, defined algebraically with primitives as \(\SE(3)\) elements, rules as composition operations, and constraints as inequalities on twists, bridging the gap between continuous joint‑angle spaces and discrete design descriptions.

\item \textbf{Contribution 4: An Expanded Pattern Language for Grasping.} A hierarchical catalogue of 20 grasp patterns at finger, hand, and task scales, documented with mathematical realizations (joint-angle ranges, force distributions, screw-theoretic grasp qualities) and design guidelines, extending existing grasp taxonomies with design-oriented documentation and restraining forces.

\item \textbf{Contribution 5: Tectonic Principles with Quantitative Proxies for Mechanical Legibility.} The first systematic application of architectural tectonics to hand design, including quantitative metrics (tendon visibility index, articulation exposure score, force flow clarity) that link mechanical expression to user acceptance and cognitive load, enabling theoretical optimization of aesthetic and functional qualities simultaneously.

\item \textbf{Contribution 6: Formal Mappings and Functorial Semantics.} A rigorous method for translating between joint‑angle descriptions and design patterns, including nearest-neighbor classification and grammar-based generation, together with a functorial formulation that reveals structure-preserving relationships between the category of design patterns and the category of kinematic submanifolds.

\item \textbf{Contribution 7: Computational Instantiation and Pareto Analysis.} A computational implementation of the framework using an open-source hand model, demonstrating the calculation of the adaptation index, simulation of underactuated grasping, and visualization of Pareto-optimal trade-offs between functional adaptation and mechanical legibility. This verifies the theoretical constructs and establishes the framework as a practical design tool.
\end{itemize}

\section{Theoretical Implications}
The integration of mathematics and design has several theoretical implications:

\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Geometry as a common language:} Geometric mechanics provides a natural bridge between the continuous world of physics and the discrete world of design patterns. The use of \(\SE(3)\) and screw theory unifies kinematic, dynamic, and grasp analyses within a single mathematical framework that also accommodates spatial grammar rules.

\item \textbf{Layered adaptability:} The concept of layered adaptability from architecture offers a framework for understanding how hands change at different timescales, from real-time grasp adaptation to long-term reconfiguration. This aligns naturally with the modular structure of port-Hamiltonian systems.

\item \textbf{Polyvalence and underactuation:} Hertzberger's polyvalence illuminates the deep purpose of underactuation—to achieve multiple functions with minimal complexity. The adaptation index quantifies polyvalence in mechanical terms, creating a bridge between architectural theory and mechanism design.

\item \textbf{Tectonics and legibility:} Tectonics reveals that mechanical design is not merely functional but also communicative, shaping user experience and acceptance. By linking tectonic proxies to cognitive load and trust, we ground aesthetic considerations in human-robot interaction research.
\end{itemize}

\section{Future Research Directions}
This theoretical work opens several avenues for further theoretical investigation:

\begin{enumerate}
\item \textbf{Computational formalization:} Develop a formal calculus for the spatial grammar that allows automated generation of hand configurations and verification of constraints, possibly using category theory or type theory. The functorial semantics sketched here could be expanded into a full categorical framework.

\item \textbf{Extension to soft robotics:} Generalize the screw-theoretic kinematics to accommodate continuous deformations in soft and continuum hands, preserving the port-Hamiltonian structure through infinite-dimensional Dirac structures. Recent work on geometric mechanics for soft robots (e.g., \citet{softrobotics2024}) could inform this extension.

\item \textbf{Integration with machine learning:} Explore how the pattern language can serve as a structured prior for learning grasping policies, enabling symbolic–continuous hybrid representations and grammar-based reinforcement learning. Geometric deep learning on Lie groups \citep{finzi2023neural} offers tools for this integration.

\item \textbf{Variable transmission mechanisms:} Extend the mathematical characterization of the coupling matrix to time-varying or state-dependent \(P(q)\), analyzing conditions for resolving the coupling–adaptation paradox through differential geometry and hybrid systems. The emergence of variable stiffness actuators (VSAs) \citep{vsa2025} provides a hardware motivation.

\item \textbf{Higher‑order tectonics:} Develop more sophisticated proxies for tectonic qualities, potentially linking them to information-theoretic measures of mechanical expression or to perceptual models from psychophysics. User studies (once hardware is available) could validate these proxies.

\item \textbf{Category‑theoretic unification:} Fully develop the adjunction between the category of kinematic models (with morphisms given by reparameterizations) and the category of design patterns (with morphisms given by pattern refinements). This could lead to a formal design language with well-defined semantics.

\item \textbf{Formal verification of grasp patterns:} Use the mathematical constraints encoded in pattern templates to automatically verify that a given hand design can achieve all required patterns, perhaps through satisfiability modulo theories (SMT) solving. This would enable design certification.

\item \textbf{Neuromorphic and soft robotics integration:} With the rise of neuromorphic control and soft materials, extend the port-Hamiltonian framework to incorporate variable impedance and embodied intelligence, allowing the framework to remain relevant for 2025–2030 hardware.
\end{enumerate}

These directions remain within the realm of theory, aiming to deepen and broaden the foundational framework established here. The ultimate goal is a comprehensive mathematical–design language that enables the creation of artificial hands which are not only functionally superior but also aesthetically pleasing, intuitively understandable, and deeply responsive to human needs—hands that are, in the fullest sense, works of both science and art.

